QuarkSum — Data Source Attribution
===================================

QuarkSum uses curated scientific data from the following sources.
All data is redistributed under fair-use for educational and
scientific purposes. No raw datasets are bundled verbatim; only
derived/processed values are included in the package.


Isotope Masses and Binding Energies
------------------------------------
Source:  IAEA Atomic Mass Data Center — AME2020
         (Atomic Mass Evaluation 2020)
Authors: W.J. Huang, M. Wang, F.G. Kondev, G. Audi, S. Naimi
DOI:     10.1088/1674-1137/abddb0
URL:     https://www-nds.iaea.org/amdc/
File:    quarksum/data/isotopes.json


Fundamental Physical Constants
-------------------------------
Source:  CODATA 2018 (Committee on Data of the International
         Science Council)
         Exact values from the 2019 SI redefinition where applicable.
URL:     https://physics.nist.gov/cuu/Constants/
File:    quarksum/core/constants.py


Quark Masses
-------------
Source:  Particle Data Group — PDG 2024 Review of Particle Physics
         MS-bar scheme central values for up and down quarks.
Authors: R.L. Workman et al. (Particle Data Group)
DOI:     10.1103/PhysRevD.110.030001
URL:     https://pdg.lbl.gov/
File:    quarksum/checksum/stoq_checksum.py (inline constants)


Element Properties
-------------------
Source:  IUPAC Periodic Table of the Elements (2021)
         NIST Atomic Spectra Database (ionization energies)
         Wikipedia (element categories, discovery dates, descriptions)
URL:     https://iupac.org/what-we-do/periodic-table-of-elements/
         https://www.nist.gov/pml/atomic-spectra-database
File:    quarksum/data/elements.json


Material Properties
--------------------
Source:  CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics (density, phase data)
         PubChem (molecular formulas, molecular weights)
         Wikipedia (material descriptions, common names)
URL:     https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/
File:    quarksum/data/materials.json
